<h1>ELK</h1>

<p>
The elk response emerges when instability creates internal suspension without direction. The system does not commit to movement, avoidance, or control; instead it remains in a paused state where action feels undefined or unclear. Instability produces stagnation rather than reaction.
</p>

<p>
Perception becomes uncertain in directional processing. The system evaluates possible actions but does not resolve them into execution, leading to extended internal hesitation during instability.
</p>

<p>
Under stress, this indecision can persist, resulting in prolonged inactivity where neither forward movement nor withdrawal fully forms.
</p>

<p>
In social environments, this manifests as hesitation, delayed response, or uncertainty in engagement direction during unstable conditions.
</p>

<p>
In environmental contexts, the system remains reactive internally but non-committal externally, leading to stalled interaction with unfolding situations.
</p>

<p>
At its most extreme expression, this becomes persistent stagnation, where action cannot resolve due to lack of internal directional clarity.
</p>

<h3>Internal Presentation</h3>
<p>
Internally, this state operates as unresolved directional conflict, where multiple possible responses exist but none are fully selected.
</p>

<h3>External Presentation</h3>
<p>
Externally, this appears as hesitation, delay, or lack of decisive movement under unstable conditions.
</p>

<h3>Influence Layer</h3>
<p>
Influence manifests as temporal stagnation. Environments exposed to this state experience slowed progression due to delayed decision activation.
</p>
